  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most sellers meet three agents, listen to three appraisals, and pick whichever number sounds most convincing. Sellers who do better than that spend a couple of hours researching their suburb's actual sales data first. It is not complicated, it does not require a paid subscription, and it changes the conversation with every agent who walks through the door.</p>

      <p>This article walks through the public data that matters, how to read it, what the headline numbers hide, and how to build a comparable sales list you can use to pressure-test pricing, challenge appraisals that seem off, and evaluate offers during the campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why sellers should research the data themselves</h2>

      <p>Three reasons. First, market research sets realistic expectations before the agents arrive. Knowing what comparable homes have actually sold for, and how long they took, means the appraisal conversation starts from shared facts rather than hope. Second, it helps you evaluate agents. An agent whose pricing matches the data and whose comparables line up with your own independent research is easier to trust. An agent whose appraisal is $150,000 above the evidence has either missed something you should understand, or is trying to win the listing with a number they cannot defend. Third, it gives you something concrete to refer back to when offers come in mid-campaign.</p>

      <p>Two hours of research at the beginning of the process reliably pays off in sharper pricing, better agent choice, and faster decision-making once offers land.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The main public data sources</h2>

      <p>Realestate.com.au and Domain both publish a sold section for each suburb, showing individual sale prices and photos of recently sold properties. Coverage is generally good for properties sold via public campaigns, less reliable for off-market and pre-auction sales. These are the two most useful free sources for most sellers.</p>

      <p>CoreLogic holds the most comprehensive property sales database in Australia. Most sellers do not subscribe directly, but your solicitor or agent can usually pull a CoreLogic property report on request. If you are considering a major sale, it is worth asking.</p>

      <p>The Queensland Valuer-General publishes annual statutory valuations for every property in the state. These valuations sit below market value and are used for rates, not sales, but the trend data is useful for understanding how land values in your area have moved over time.</p>

      <p>Brisbane City Council data portals provide property attributes (lot size, zoning, overlays, building footprint) and can confirm the facts you want to include in your campaign. The City Plan 2014 mapping tool is the most useful, and it is free.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the headline suburb statistics tell you</h2>

      <p>Four numbers get quoted most often in suburb profiles. The median sale price and its twelve-month movement give a sense of the broad price level and trend. Days on market, the time from listing to contract, indicates how competitive the buyer pool has been. Auction clearance rate, if the suburb is auction-heavy, is a leading indicator of buyer depth. Sales volume, the number of sales compared to the prior period, shows whether activity is picking up or slowing down.</p>

      <p>These are useful at a glance, but they are aggregate numbers across a whole suburb. They almost never reflect what your specific property will do.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What headline statistics hide</h2>

      <p>The median blurs the difference between a two-bedroom unit and a four-bedroom house. A suburb with a $1.4 million median may have houses transacting between $1.8 million and $2.5 million and units transacting between $600,000 and $900,000. Always filter by property type and bedroom count before trusting a median as a benchmark for your property.</p>

      <p>A median moving up can reflect composition change, not genuine growth. If the mix of properties sold this quarter skews more heavily to larger homes than the prior quarter, the median rises even if no individual property has increased in value. A median moving down during a quiet period can be a similar statistical artefact when fewer premium homes transact.</p>

      <p>Days on market and clearance rate can lag. They reflect what happened thirty to ninety days ago, not what is happening now. For the freshest read on the market, look at how many properties are currently on the market, how many open homes ran last weekend, and how the most recent contracts were negotiated, which requires conversation with an active agent.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Building a comparable sales list</h2>

      <p>A comparable sales list is the single most useful piece of research a seller can build. The goal is to identify five to ten properties sold in the last six months that closely match yours on the attributes buyers actually price on.</p>

      <p>Match on property type first (house, townhouse, apartment). Match on bedroom and bathroom count next. Then match on floor area or land area, depending on whether you are selling a house or a unit. Finally, think about aspect, street context, and any obvious differentiators such as pool, renovation, or view. The closer the match, the more useful the comparable.</p>

      <p>For each comparable, write down the sale price, the days on market, the campaign method (auction, private treaty, off-market), and anything visible about the property's condition from the photos. This list will be more useful than any suburb-wide statistic when you are deciding whether an offer is strong or whether an agent's appraisal stacks up.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What comparable data cannot tell you</h2>

      <p>Sale prices are outcomes, not proof of fair value. A comparable's result depends on factors that are invisible from the outside. How hard the buyer pushed for the price matters: a stressed seller's outcome may not reflect what a well-prepared seller can achieve. How the campaign was run matters: a weak campaign with poor photography and a short marketing window may have left money on the table. Non-visible features (interior condition, renovation quality, defects) affect price in ways that photos rarely reveal.</p>

      <p>Another trap is the auction pass-in. Public data often shows the pass-in price as the sale price, but the property can close higher or lower later when the sale is completed privately. If a comparable was passed in at auction, verify the actual sale price with the agent or via the seller's solicitor before using it to benchmark your own property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The three, five, and ten-year view</h2>

      <p>Do not rely on a single year's growth number. A twelve-month figure can be distorted by one or two premium sales, by a particularly hot summer, or by construction cost changes that affect new-build pricing. Always check three-year, five-year, and ten-year compound growth alongside the twelve-month figure.</p>

      <p>Long-term growth is a better indicator of what your property may fetch than a hot twelve-month period. If the suburb has grown at 5 per cent compound over ten years but 12 per cent in the last twelve months, you are probably at a cyclical high. If it has grown at 7 per cent over ten years but only 2 per cent in the last twelve months, you are probably at a cyclical low. Both matter when you decide timing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Using the research in agent meetings</h2>

      <p>When an agent presents their appraisal, ask them to walk you through their comparable sales. A good agent will already have a list and will explain why each one is relevant, how it differs from your property, and how the differences translate into price. Compare their list to yours. If there is significant overlap and their price range sits broadly where your research puts it, that is a good sign.</p>

      <p>If the agent's appraisal is materially above the evidence, ask them to explain the difference. Sometimes they know about an off-market sale that has not reached the public data, or a specific feature of your property that commands a premium. That can be a legitimate reason for a higher number. Sometimes they are simply overpricing to win the listing, and the campaign will discount back to market in the first month. A seller who has done their own research can tell the difference.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Using the research during the campaign</h2>

      <p>Once the property is listed, the research becomes a reference point for evaluating offers. A first offer that sits five per cent below the middle of your comparable range is reasonable and worth working with. An offer that sits twenty per cent below is either a low opportunistic bid or a signal the market has shifted since the research was done, and is worth checking against recent activity.</p>

      <p>If the property is taking longer than the suburb's typical days on market, the research helps diagnose why. Too few comparables sold recently may mean the buyer pool is thin. Sales closing below the medians may mean your price guide is too high. Having the data on hand makes these mid-campaign conversations with your agent concrete rather than speculative.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>

      <p>Sellers who invest time researching suburb data make better pricing and agent decisions. The investment is modest: two hours of browsing realestate.com.au, Domain, and the council mapping tool, plus a spreadsheet with five to ten comparable sales. The return is sharper conversations with agents, a more defensible list price, and faster, more confident decision-making once offers land.</p>

      <p>Use the public data as a foundation. Refine it with comparable sales that match your property on the attributes buyers actually price on. Bring the research to every agent meeting, and keep it close during the campaign. The data does not make the decision for you, but it gives you something solid to stand on when the decisions get hard.</p>

